Titanic_ML:¶

Ronen Saviz, ID 205688690
https://www.kaggle.com/savizronen

Introduction¶

  • This competition is about trying to predict if a passenger survived the sinking of the Titanic or not.
  • Starting from dataset understanding, up until machine learning model training and evaluation.

Data Description¶

  • Dataset Summary - Titanic passenger details, including a column if the survived passenger survived or not.
  • Index Column (Instance of what we want to predict for) - PassengerId.
  • Target Column (What we want to predict for each element in Index Column) - Survived.
  • Features - Remaining Columns.

Tasks¶

  • Our target is to learn the "t" function.
  • This case is about binary classification (Survived or not), therefore it will be performed by using "Logistic Regression".
  • After the learning process, a new data will be tested with our model to determine who's going to be survived and who isn't.

# Prints the amount of empty values in each value.
def count_empty_values_in_each_column(df):
    code = "len(np.where(df[column].isnull())[0])"
    for column in df.columns:
        print(f'`{column}`: {eval(code)}')
# Prints the amount of empty values in each value in train and test of the ML.
def print_count_empty_values_in_each_column(train,test):
    print(" Data train empty values in each column:")
    count_empty_values_in_each_column(train)
    print("-----------------")
    print(" Data test empty values in each column:")
    count_empty_values_in_each_column(test)

Cleaning operations:

In [7]:
#Changes the names to titles.
def title_name(data):
    return  Title_Dictionary[data['Name'].split(',')[1].split('.')[0].strip()]

# Filling all cols in a mean value.
def filling_cols_in_a_mean_value(data,cols):
    for col in cols:
        data[col].fillna(data[col].mean(), inplace=True)
    return data

# Filling the empty value column with 'U' (Unknown).
def filling_empty_value_in_unknown_val(data,value):
    data[value].fillna('U', inplace=True)
    return data

#Drop selected features.
def drop_features(data,features):
    return data.drop(features, axis=1)

#Keeping the first letter in a feature.
def Keeping_the_first_letter_in_a_feature(data,feature):
    for i in range(len(data[feature])):
         data[feature].replace(data[feature][i], data[feature][i][0], inplace=True)
    return data
In [8]:
#Cleaning the data.
def clean(data):  
    
    #Creation a Title for every person.
    data['Title']=data.apply(title_name, axis = 1)

    filling_empty_value_in_unknown_val(data,"Cabin")
    
    #Filling the empty cols with 'U' (Unknown).
    cols = ["Fare", "Age","SibSp", "Parch"]  
    data = filling_cols_in_a_mean_value(data,cols)

    #Keeping the first letter, which makes the column's values to be divided by zones.
    Keeping_the_first_letter_in_a_feature(data,"Cabin")

    #Drop all the unimportant features.
    unimportant_features=["PassengerId", "Ticket","Embarked","Name"]
    data = drop_features(data,unimportant_features)
    
    return data 

train = clean(train)
test = clean(test)

Encoding features by one hot encoder:

In [20]:
#Encoding sex by one hot encoder.
def one_hot_encoder_sex(data,encoder):
    encoder_title = pd.DataFrame(encoder.fit_transform(data[['Sex']]).toarray())
    encoder_title.columns = ['Female' ,'Male']
    data = data.join(encoder_title)
    return data

#Encoding Title by one hot encoder.
def one_hot_encoder_title(data,encoder):
    encoder_title = pd.DataFrame(encoder.fit_transform(data[['Title']]).toarray())
    encoder_title.columns = ['Master', 'Miss', 'Mr' ,'Mrs', 'Royalty' ,'Officer']
    data = data.join(encoder_title)
    return data

#Encoding Cabin by one hot encoder.
def one_hot_encoder_cabin(data,encoder):
    le = preprocessing.LabelEncoder()
    data['Cabin']= le.fit_transform(data['Cabin'])
    return data

#Activation of all encoder operations.
def one_hot_encoder(data):
    encoder = OneHotEncoder(handle_unknown='ignore')
    data=one_hot_encoder_sex(data,encoder)
    data=one_hot_encoder_title(data,encoder)
    one_hot_encoder_cabin(data,encoder)
    data=data.drop('Title', axis=1)
    return  data.drop('Sex', axis=1)

train=one_hot_encoder(train)
test=one_hot_encoder(test)

Apply hypers on the data:

In [22]:
#Calculating the price of a class ticket.
def fare_per_pclass(data):
    return data['Fare']/data['Pclass']

#Check if a person has a family.
def has_family(data):
    has_family=1 if  ((data['SibSp'] + data['Parch'])  > 0) else 0
    return has_family

#classification a person age range.
def age_range(data):
    if 0 <= data['Age'] <= 16:
        age_range = 0
    if 16 < data['Age'] <= 32:
        age_range = 1
    if 32 < data['Age'] <= 48:
        age_range = 2
    if 48 < data['Age'] <= 64:
        age_range = 3
    if 64 < data['Age']:
        age_range = 4
    return age_range

#Update the data by hypers.
def apply_hypers(data):
    data['Family'] = data.apply(has_family, axis = 1)
    data['FarePerPclass'] = data.apply(fare_per_pclass, axis = 1)
    data['Age_range'] = data.apply(age_range, axis = 1)
    
apply_hypers(train)
apply_hypers(test)
